# PART ONE — Kipling, "If—"

## 1. The Poem

Rudyard Kipling, "If—" (written c. 1895; first published 1910 in *Rewards and Fairies*). Cast throughout as a single conditional sentence: a long chain of *if*-clauses whose grammatical resolution — the main clause — is withheld until the final two lines.

> If you can keep your head when all about you
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Are losing theirs and blaming it on you,
> If you can trust yourself when all men doubt you,
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;But make allowance for their doubting too;
> If you can wait and not be tired by waiting,
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Or being lied about, don't deal in lies,
> Or being hated, don't give way to hating,
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And yet don't look too good, nor talk too wise:
>
> If you can dream—and not make dreams your master;
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If you can think—and not make thoughts your aim;
> If you can meet with Triumph and Disaster
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And treat those two impostors just the same;
> If you can bear to hear the truth you've spoken
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Twisted by knaves to make a trap for fools,
> Or watch the things you gave your life to, broken,
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And stoop and build 'em up with worn-out tools:
>
> If you can make one heap of all your winnings
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And risk it on one turn of pitch-and-toss,
> And lose, and start again at your beginnings
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And never breathe a word about your loss;
> If you can force your heart and nerve and sinew
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;To serve your turn long after they are gone,
> And so hold on when there is nothing in you
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Except the Will which says to them: "Hold on!"
>
> If you can talk with crowds and keep your virtue,
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Or walk with Kings—nor lose the common touch,
> If neither foes nor loving friends can hurt you,
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;If all men count with you, but none too much;
> If you can fill the unforgiving minute
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;With sixty seconds' worth of distance run,
> Yours is the Earth and everything that's in it,
> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;And—which is more—you'll be a Man, my son!

---

## 2. Situating the Reading

"If—" is among the most quoted poems in the English language, which has earned it a certain critical suspicion: a poem so widely recited as moral instruction is easily mistaken for nothing but moral instruction — a versified list of virtues, an H₄₈-level artifact of advice. The structural reading sets that reception aside and asks the single question the method asks of any document (Paper 10½, §9): not what it recommends, but what shape it takes.

The shape is the first thing to notice, and it is not the shape of a list. A list has no developmental necessity — its items can be reordered without loss. "If—" cannot be reordered without loss, and the reason is that the poem is built as a single suspended conditional: dozens of *if*-clauses whose main clause does not arrive until the final couplet. The whole poem is a sentence held open, under grammatical tension, waiting for a resolution it refuses to grant until the end. That suspension is a developmental structure, not an enumerative one. The poem is an octave whose returning Do is grammatically withheld, and the withholding is the engine of the reading.

---

## 3. The Law of Three

Every genuine truth-work exhibits the triadic structure Active / Passive / Reconciling — not as imposed scheme but as the organizational necessity that results whenever ⟨·,·⟩ shapes a work (Paper 10, §3). The method of "If—" is unusually transparent about its own triadic core, because the poem's recurring move *is* a Law-of-Three operation, performed again and again on different material.

The poem's signature gesture is the holding of two opposed forces in one frame without letting either collapse the other. It is stated most baldly at the poem's center — "If you can meet with Triumph and Disaster / And treat those two impostors just the same" — but it governs every clause:

| Role | Structural element | Textual instances |
|---|---|---|
| **Active** | The affirming pole: the force that asserts, reaches, drives — trust, dreaming, thinking, winning, willing, the heart that forces its own continuation | "trust yourself"; "dream"; "think"; "make one heap of all your winnings"; "the Will which says... 'Hold on!'" |
| **Passive** | The denying pole: the resisting force that would, left alone, overwhelm — doubt, loss, hatred, the lie, the broken work, the crowd, the King | "all men doubt you"; "being hated"; "lose, and start again"; "the things you gave your life to, broken"; "crowds"; "Kings" |
| **Reconciling** | The third, neutralizing force that holds the two without merging them: the qualification clause — *and yet*, *but*, *nor*, *—and not* — that keeps each pole from becoming master | "But make allowance for their doubting too"; "and not make dreams your master"; "treat those two impostors just the same"; "nor lose the common touch"; "but none too much" |

This is the structurally decisive observation about the poem, and it is exact: the Reconciling term in "If—" is almost always a single conjunction or qualifying clause. The poem does not resolve its oppositions by choosing a side, nor by averaging them into a bland mean. It holds them — *dream, and not make dreams your master*; *think, and not make thoughts your aim*; *all men count with you, but none too much*. The neutralizing third force is the refusal to let either the affirming or the denying pole become absolute. Triumph and Disaster are not weighed against each other; they are *both* named impostors, and the equanimity that calls them so is the third term that neither of them could generate.

This is the Triamazikamno performed as a discipline of attention: not the suppression of the two forces but their reconciliation by a third that is genuinely distinct from both. A poem that merely advised stoic indifference would have no Reconciling term — it would have an Active virtue (composure) asserted against a Passive world, with no third force, and would read as flat assertion (the failure mode of Paper 10, §3). "If—" does not assert composure; it specifies, line by line, the exact qualification that holds each opposition open. That qualification is the work the poem is doing, and it is Law-of-Three work.

