## 4. The Law of Seven: Stage Analysis

The Law of Seven is not "seven parts." It is a developmental shape (Paper 10, §4): a process that begins from a ground, develops by internal logic to the point where internal logic stalls, receives an input it could not generate, develops the new content, approaches completion, and then requires a volitional act to return to the tonic at a higher octave. The reading must find that shape, and find its two interval positions, not merely partition the text into seven boxes.

The prior H₄₈ formal constraint here is the poem's four-octave stanzaic structure and, more importantly, its grammatical structure: one suspended conditional sentence. The developmental arc inhabits and reshapes that constraint. The seven stages are the stages of the conditional's progression toward its withheld main clause, and the two intervals fall exactly where the conditional changes its character.

### Stage Table

| Stage | Label | Text region | Structural content |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Do** | Ground stated | "If you can keep your head when all about you / Are losing theirs..." | The tonic of the whole poem: self-command under external pressure. Every later trial is a development of this one note — the holding of one's own state against a contrary field. Not yet the hardest case; the establishing case. |
| **Re** | First development | "If you can trust yourself when all men doubt you, / But make allowance for their doubting too" | The first articulation of the poem's method — self-trust immediately qualified by the Reconciling clause. The Do's bare self-command is refined into the poem's characteristic doubled move. |
| **Mi** | Internal elaboration | "If you can wait and not be tired... / Or being lied about, don't deal in lies, / Or being hated, don't give way to hating, / And yet don't look too good, nor talk too wise" | The elaboration of self-command into its fuller demands — patience, integrity, restraint — still proceeding by the same internal logic: the self governing the self against an adverse world. This is the limit of what self-command alone can specify. |
| **〈Mi-Fa gap〉** | The qualitative crossing: self-command alone reaches its ceiling | The turn into stanza two: "If you can dream—and not make dreams your master; / If you can think—and not make thoughts your aim; / If you can meet with Triumph and Disaster / And treat those two impostors just the same" | **The first shock. Through the Mi stage the trials are trials of holding the self steady against an outer pressure — the kind of thing the will can, in principle, command. At the Mi-Fa interval the poem crosses into a different order of trial: the governing of the inner faculties themselves (dream, thought) and the equanimity before Triumph and Disaster that cannot be willed into existence by the self that wants it. "Treat those two impostors just the same" names a stance that self-command cannot produce, because the self that has just triumphed is *changed* by the triumph; the equanimity must come from a register the willing self does not control. This is the input from outside the system the poem had been developing — the recognition that the hardest trials are not of strength but of a detachment the strong self cannot supply for itself.** |
| **Fa** | The new content developed | "If you can bear to hear the truth you've spoken / Twisted by knaves... / Or watch the things you gave your life to, broken, / And stoop and build 'em up with worn-out tools" | The Fa-content: what the Mi-Fa crossing makes possible. These are no longer trials of holding steady but of *continuing after loss that the self did not deserve and cannot reverse* — rebuilding broken work with worn-out tools. The composure of the impostors-clause is now applied to genuine ruin. |
| **Sol** | Development of the development | "If you can make one heap of all your winnings / And risk it on one turn of pitch-and-toss, / And lose, and start again at your beginnings / And never breathe a word about your loss" | The Fa-content carried to its sharpest form: total loss, freely risked, borne in silence. The detachment received at Mi-Fa is now exercised at the scale of everything. |
| **La** | Approach to completion | "If you can force your heart and nerve and sinew / To serve your turn long after they are gone, / And so hold on when there is nothing in you / Except the Will which says to them: 'Hold on!'" | The penultimate stage: the will exercised past the body's capacity, holding when there is "nothing in you." The full arc is in view — but note that this culminating image of the *will* is still inside the list. The poem has reached the limit of what the conditional clauses, however heroic, can specify. It has not yet turned. |
| **〈Si-Do gap〉** | The qualitative crossing: the turn the list cannot generate | The final stanza's last movement: "If you can fill the unforgiving minute / With sixty seconds' worth of distance run, / **Yours is the Earth...**" — and the turn to direct address | **The second shock, and the structurally decisive one. Through every preceding stage the poem is a chain of conditions, accumulating without resolving — grammatically, a sentence held open. The "unforgiving minute" filled with "sixty seconds' worth of distance run" is the last condition, and it is the smallest: not a heap of winnings or a lifetime's work but a single minute lived completely. Then the conditional breaks. The main clause arrives — "Yours is the Earth and everything that's in it" — the resolution the whole poem has withheld. But this resolution cannot be generated by adding one more *if*. No quantity of conditions completes a conditional; the completion is of a different kind from the items it completes. The arrival of the main clause is the volitional turn the Si-Do interval names: the grammatical release that the list of clauses could approach forever and never reach by accumulation.** |
| **Do (return)** | Resolution at a higher octave | "And—which is more—you'll be a Man, my son!" | The returning tonic — but transformed, and addressed. The poem began impersonally ("If *you* can...") and ends with a relation: *my son*. The completion is not "Yours is the Earth" — that is named and then surpassed ("which is more"). The true Do-return is the turn from the catalogue of conditions to the single addressee, the son who is the reason the catalogue was ever spoken. The ground returns at the higher octave: the self-command of the opening Do is revealed, at the close, to have been all along an address from one person to another. |

