## 5. Interval Positions

### 5.1 The Mi-Fa Gap

The Mi-Fa interval is the place where automatic continuation fails and content must enter from outside the system the work has been developing (Paper 10, §5). In "If—" the development through Do, Re, and Mi proceeds by a single internal logic: the self holding itself steady against an outer pressure. Keeping one's head, trusting oneself, waiting without tiring, not returning the lie or the hatred — these are all, in principle, achievable by an act of self-command. They are the same operation applied to harder material.

At the turn into the second stanza that logic reaches its ceiling and a different order of trial enters. "Treat those two impostors just the same" cannot be reached by intensifying self-command, because the obstacle is no longer the outer field but the inner alteration that triumph and disaster work *on the self that would command*. The equanimity required is not more of the same will; it is a detachment the willing self cannot manufacture, precisely because it is the willing self that has been moved. This is the structural signature of the Mi-Fa shock: the recognition that the next stage is not harder-of-the-same-kind but other-in-kind, and that it requires something the preceding effort cannot supply. The poem does not announce the crossing; it enacts it, by shifting without warning from trials of fortitude to trials of detachment. The "impostors" line is the input from above — the recognition that triumph is as much a danger to the self as disaster, which the fortitude of the first stanza could never have generated on its own.

### 5.2 The Si-Do Gap

The Si-Do interval is the place where understanding is insufficient and a volitional act is required — where the conclusion must be affirmed, not calculated (Paper 10, §5). In "If—" this position is held by the most conspicuous formal feature of the poem: its grammar.

The entire poem is a conditional sentence with no main clause until the end. Every stanza adds conditions; the protasis grows and grows; the apodosis is withheld. This is not a stylistic flourish — it is the Si-Do gap rendered as syntax. A conditional can be extended indefinitely by adding clauses; what it cannot do is *complete itself* by adding one more clause, because the completion belongs to a different grammatical order than the conditions. The main clause, when it finally arrives — "Yours is the Earth" — is not the last and largest *if*. It is the release of the suspension, the act that no quantity of *ifs* could perform. The reader who has been waiting through the whole accumulating sentence feels the resolution arrive as a thing of a different kind: not earned by the list but granted at its end.

And then the poem does the thing the Si-Do interval most precisely describes: it does not rest in the calculated reward. "Yours is the Earth and everything that's in it" is the kind of completion the list could in principle motivate — possession, mastery, the world as prize. The poem names it and immediately surpasses it: "And—which is more—you'll be a Man, my son." The final turn is volitional, not calculated. The catalogue of trials could justify the inheritance of the Earth; it cannot generate the turn to the son. That turn is an act of address — the revelation that the whole impersonal sequence was, from the first line, spoken *to someone*, in love, by a father. The completion is chosen, not derived: the poem elects, at the last possible instant, to be a relation rather than a reward. That election is the Si-Do act.

